passages.text: As kids (and the market) head back from their respective summer vacations, below are some of the larger tests the Lev Fin universe will face into September (with many other pop quizzes to assuredly arise, too).

Simply from my seat: fundamentals remain strong, but the tails should continue to be minded. The left as valuations remain challenged and technicals may shift, the right aided by an M&A- friendly environment

- Valuation constraints. Coming into the year, credit valuations were stretched with USD HY spreads trading in their 4 percentile on a lookback basis to 2000 (double-Bs: 2 nd single-Bs: 4 nd triple-Cs: 12 nd Today? Despite the recent slowdown in growth and the renewed focus on tariffs, valuations are even tighter than they were to start 2025 as HY bond yields have ratcheted-in to their 40-month lows with HY spreads sitting in the 2 nd percentile (double-Bs: 2 nd single-Bs: 3 nd triple-Cs: 18 nd)

- Fundamentals are largely to thank: with nearly all of the S&P 500 having reported, S&P 500 EPS grew 11% YoY, clearing the low 4% hurdle set by consensus estimates. Net profit margins for the median USD HY issuer expanded, showing more resilience to tariffs than feared. Debt service capacity also improved, easing concerns over issuers' abilities to adapt to higher funding costs. While 2025 has been the fastest year to surpass 25 \$1bn+ bankruptcy filings since 2020, holistic default rates have remained manageable, especially when excluding LMEs from the calculation

- Primary supply 
- two sides to the coin

- After a summer full of opportunistic primary deals, a continued pick-up in new money issuance is not a matter of if, but rather when Consider: 1) 2025 is currently tracking right behind 2021 as the strongest year for strategic M&A transactions in North America with banks having just signed up their largest acquisition-related bridge in the US market this year 31,32; LFI's "net net" calendar (which strips out all pending repayments from visible supply) recently returned to positive territory after being deeply in the red during the summer; and 3) the previous metric is unlikely to flip in September 
- particularly in the HY market 
- as the month's historically large issuance number has outweighed respective coupons and principal returns by the most of any month

- Last year, issuance doubled from August (\$18bn) to September (\$37bn). Other Septembers historically have also included large totals like \$44bn in 2021, \$47bn in 2020, and \$48bn in 2013 (for context, 2025's monthly average has been \$25.7bn)
- That being said, the market is mostly ready for a pick-up in issuance
- Why? 1) many transactions have been well-telegraphed: GIR highlighted that there is typically a meaningful delay between the announcement and the

actual completion of deals. For strategic deals announced in 2024, the average length of time to completion was more than six months; 2) even if opportunistic issuers are eager to try their hand in the currently accommodative primary, Capital Markets desks have historically been in no rush to re- open the market. Going back to 2015, the average first week of business following Labor Day has seen issuance track \(\sim 49\%\) lower than what the market was run rating at during this year' s ferrous July and August pace where \(\) 8bn\(of weekly HY primary issuance was surpassed for nine straight weeks' and furthermore, 3) looking back over the last month, multiple Lev Fin issuers have actually been beneficiaries of M&A transactions, providing an unexpected boost to investor returns
September's homework: stay invested, add hedges...and M&A upside

1. Stay invested: there is still a chance that despite a pick-up in supply, valuations could continue to remain stretched and we grind from here: on a 20y lookback, when HY cash crosses the \(10^{\text{th}}\) percentile barrier, it has stayed there for an average of 85 trading sessions. We' re currently at 61 (h/t Reid Zhou)
20y lookback on how long we hold when HY spreads are within their \(10^{\text{th}}\) percentile

2. Mind the tails. First the left: 1) it is impossible to ignore that the second half of September is the worst two-week period of the year for equities and the VIX is coming off its largest 20-week decline in history. Scan GS Credit Strat Reid Zhou's recent piece for some low-cost hedges/expressions that could merit adding; 2) as GIR noted in their most recent Credit Trader, dispersion has remained high across Lev Fin, but a large portion of that metric continues to be driven by lower-quality issuers. 101 issuers fall into the top decile of the USD HY index constituents ranked by spread, but only 10 issuers account for 38% of the total par value of the bonds outstanding. Those 10 largest issuers have a median net leverage ratio of 7.9x while five of the ten have negative interest coverage ratios However, all "higher-quality" issuers are not immune as is evident by the pullback seen in cyclical sectors, many in spite of their higher ratings profiles. Yes, the impending Fed cuts could help the economics of certain issuers' refinancing challenges, but with current yields for CCCs sitting 250bps above their maturing coupon levels, caution around cyclical risk in the USD HY market (ratings agnostic) and towards CCCs in general should continue to be heeded
Source: GIR's Shamshad Ali

3. ...then the right: as previously mentioned, many Lev Fin issuers have been the beneficiaries of the recent ramp in M&A activity. Some notable movers over the last month, driven by asset sales or straight M&A: COMM +2pts, FBM +7.25pts, DISH +13.5pts, VTLE +13-14pts, and SHLFD1 +20.125pts- Note that many of these are 1) lower-rated credits; 2) capital structures that were meaningfully underweight by the real money community; and/or 3) popular shorts by the faster-money investor base. As a result, the technicals further exaggerated the relative performances and catalyzed more compressionary portfolio decisions. Reach out to compare notes with our analyst team on other names we think fit the same mold, going into the Fall

- There are now 498 AI "unicorns" or private companies valued at \$1bn or more which have a combined value of \$2.7tn- America's top companies have mentioned "recession" (and related synonyms) just 273x on calls this quarter, down from 862 in Q1...- The number of consumer discretionary and consumer staples retailers with more than \$100MM in liabilities that filed a "chapter 22" since 2016 is now up to 15- Nearly \$19bn of renewable energy projects have been cancelled this year, a 2,149% increase YoY- Existing homes are now more expensive than new homes for just the second time over the last 25+ years- WalletHub is out with the best states to live...and for a second year in a row Massachusetts topped the list with Idaho, NJ, Wisconsin, and MN rounding out the top-5- The International Air Transport Association put out its 2024 "year in review" report. Some notables: 1) the US has the most air travelers in the world with 876MM, followed by 741MM in China, and then the UK with 261MM; 2) 9 of the 10 busiest flight routes were in Asia; and 3) the Boeing 737 Max completed 10MM flights in 2024 - the most popular plane globally- Despite my family's efforts to keep a never-ending pile of Amazon boxes on our doorstep, corrugated cardboard shipments fell to their lowest Q2 levels since 2015- AOL announced that it's pulling the plug...finally...on dial-up internet on September 30. In 1999, the company had more than 18MM subscribers. By 2021, the number was in the low thousands. Goodbye- Looking for Valentine's Day plans for next year? Taco Bell announced that for just \$777 you can get married in their Las Vegas chapel with a bouquet of hot sauces

- With the US Open underway, many records are surely to be broken. Potentially the most important: Honey Deuce consumption. Last year, 556k were sold at \(\)23/\$ pop (1 every 1.5 seconds), bringing in \(12.8MM in revenues\)^{19} 
- Lastly, Lee Corso made his final appearance on ESPN's College GameDay with the 90 year old former coach making his 431 headgear pick - a tradition he started doing in 1996 for each week's most impactful game. His final choice - the headgear of OSU's Brutus Buckeye - proved to the right one, cementing his impressive record at 287-144^{17}
- September's seasonality has proven to be a headwind for IG and HY as gross issuance ramps...but a modest one...
Source: Bloomberg, Goldman Sachs Global Investment Research

to come to market, the next few months could see a robust pick- up in bonds earmarked for M&A \(^{25}\)

- Finally, with the NFL restarting its regular season this upcoming week, Sportico completed its annual NFL franchise valuation ranking. The Dallas Cowboys remain atop the list (even post their Micah Parsons trade) – worth \(\) 12.8bn\(with the Rams and Giants also receiving\) \ \(10bn+\) valuations

(\$10.4bn and \$10.3bn, respectively). It's notable that since the NFL decided to open up the league to PE, franchise valuation estimates have risen by 20% on average over the past 12 months. Touchdown!

Global Credit Trader: The dispersion aspersion Global Markets Daily: Why the Rally Has Been Much Broader in Credit Than in Equity US Economics Analyst: Earnings Season Takeaways: Adjusting to the New Environment US Economics Analyst: Slower Job Growth Makes the Case for a Cut We suspect that weak job growth and concern about further downward revisions and downside risks have already convinced the Fed leadership to resume rate cuts. Job growth is likely to look mediocre in coming months as well due to subdued activity growth and special factors including federal government workforce reductions, the loss of Temporary Protected Status, and tighter immigration enforcement. This should support our forecast of three 25bp cuts in September, October, and December, followed by two more next year. A larger 50bp cut is also possible but would require a larger rise in the unemployment rate or worse payrolls numbers than we expect
